-- China Life, HSBC, Merchants Bank, PetroChina: Hong Kong Equities Preview
-- Saiyu Zhou
-- 2010-06-24T01:21:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-24/china-life-hsbc-merchants-bank-petrochina-hong-kong-equities-preview.html

          
          
             The  following  companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  
 The  Hang Seng Index  gained 0.2 percent to 20,856.61. The
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, declined 0.3 percent to 12,020.38.  
 Banks: U.K. Chancellor of the Exchequer  George Osborne  said
lenders need to share the pain of tax increases as he announced
a levy on lenders’ balance sheets. The levy is equivalent to 7
percent of the 28 billion pound ($42 billion) combined profit
analysts expect  HSBC Holdings Plc  (5 HK), Barclays Plc, Royal
Bank of Scotland Group Plc, Lloyds Banking Group Plc and
 Standard Chartered Plc  (2888 HK) to report in 2011, according to
data compiled by Bloomberg.  
 HSBC, Europe’s largest bank by market value, climbed 0.9
percent to HK$76.40. Standard Chartered, the U.K. bank that
earns three-quarters of its profit in Asia, gained 0.4 percent
to HK$205.40.  
 Insurers: China’s insurance premiums rose 36 percent in the
first five months of this year to 673.7 billion yuan ($98.9
billion), said  Shi Hong , deputy director of the China Insurance
Regulatory Commission’s general office.  
 China Life Insurance Co.  (2628 HK), the nation’s biggest
insurer, was unchanged at HK$35.90.  Ping An Insurance (Group) Co. 
(2318 HK), the No. 2, rose 1.1 percent to HK$67.15.  
 China Merchants Bank Co.  (3968 HK): The bank won’t consider
more equity financing before 2012, the China Securities Journal
reported yesterday, citing a company capital management plan.
The stock fell 0.7 percent to HK$19.42.  
 PetroChina Co.  (857 HK): China’s audit office found
irregularities in contracts signed for part of a 142.2 billion
yuan natural gas pipeline being built by PetroChina’s parent,
China National Petroleum Corp. The stock slid 0.7 percent to
HK$9.10.  
